  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Prison Sentences\n- Up to 20 years imprisonment per offense\n- Potential enhanced sentences for repeat offenses\n- Longer sentences if laundering involves more serious underlying crimes\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potentially hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars\n- Forfeitures of assets involved in the laundering\n\n3. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Professional licensing restrictions\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, criminal history, and specific circumstances of the offense. Prosecution typically occurs under statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act.\n\nThese are general legal details based on current federal statutes. For precise guidance about a specific situation, consulting a qualified legal professional is recommended.",
